{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b6273199-d520-41d3-8e35-5ffaef46b3e6","content":"## What's happening\n\n.NET periodically raises the **x86-64 microarchitecture baseline**. .NET 10 required **x86-64-v2** (SSE4.2, POPCNT — circa 2008+ CPUs). .NET 11 likely raised it to **x86-64-v3**, which requires:\n\n- **AVX2, FMA, BMI1, BMI2, F16C, LZCNT, MOVBE**\n- These debuted with Intel **Haswell (2013)** / AMD **Excavator (2015)**\n\nYour 2012-era hardware (Sandy Bridge / Ivy Bridge) has AVX but **not AVX2 or FMA**, so the runtime refuses to start.\n\n## Your other platforms are fine\n\n| Target | Architecture | Status |\n|---|---|---|\n| Linux x86-64 (2012 hw) | x86-64-v2 only | ❌ **Fails** — missing v3 instructions |\n| Windows Arm64 (SQ1) | ARMv8.2-A | ✅ Unaffected — separate ARM64 baseline |\n| Raspberry Pi 4 | ARMv8.0-A (Cortex-A72) | ✅ Unaffected — separate ARM64 baseline |\n\n## Options\n\n1. **Replace the 2012 hardware** with Haswell-era or newer (2013+).\n2. **Stay on .NET 10** (LTS) for those specific nodes until hardware is refreshed.\n3. Check if .NET 11 publishes a **v2-baseline build** of the runtime (unlikely for the default SDK, but community builds sometimes exist).\n\nYou can verify a node's support by running:\n```bash\n# Check for AVX2 support\ngrep -q avx2 /proc/cpuinfo && echo \"v3 OK\" || echo \"v3 MISSING\"\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c0592722-344c-4a9b-985e-724f6617f15f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's hardware requirements, so I can answer directly without needing to search code.\n\nThe key issue: Starting with .NET 10 (or potentially .NET 9+), Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline. Let me think about this carefully.\n\nActually, let me recall the specifics:\n\n- .NET 8 and earlier: x86-64 baseline (SSE, SSE2 - the original x86-64 minimum)\n\n\n- .NET 9/10 and beyond: There were discussions about raising the baseline to include newer instruction sets. The x86-64 microarchitecture levels define different tiers—v1 is the original baseline with SSE/SSE2, while v2 adds SSE3 through SSE4.2 and other instructions from the Nehalem/Westmere era around 2008-2010, and v3 introduces AVX, AVX2, BMI, and FMA support.\n\nThe rest of v3 includes F16C, LZCNT, and MOVBE from the Haswell generation in 2013, while v4 brings AVX-512 support. Since the user mentioned hardware from 2012, that's Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge era—capable of SSE4.2 (v2 level) and partial AVX support, but lacking AVX2, BMI, and FMA which arrived with Haswell. In .NET 10 specifically, Microsoft raised the baseline to x86-64-v2, which would require at minimum SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT support. So the most likely scenario is that .NET 11 bumped the baseline to x86-64-v3, which requires AVX2, FMA, and other instruction sets that only arrived with Haswell in 2013 and later AMD processors—that's why 2012 hardware like Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge would fail to run it. The ARM64 platforms should be fine since .NET's baseline for ARM is ARMv8.0-A, which both the Surface Pro X and Raspberry Pi 4 support. The real issue is that .NET 11 likely raised the x86-64 baseline from v2 to v3, requiring Haswell-era features like AVX2 and FMA that older hardware doesn't have. I should focus on explaining what happened and what the user's options are rather than speculating about .NET 11's exact requirements.","outputTokens":1802,"requestId":"B821:E621D:A8F1854:B818074:69FD3FC4"},"id":"e5839b49-dfee-4267-b46b-fbe9d52fc13f","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:44:09.401Z","parentId":"2af23024-0c81-44a5-b4da-170f8cfd94e5"}
